cms.contentitemcommondata.ContentItemCommonDataVisualBuilderWidget:
    {"editableAreas":[{"identifier":"BlogPost","sections":[{"identifier":"9ff8ec95-7f18-4213-820a-e82c27aff000","type":"Goldfinch.ContentSection","properties":{"sectionID":"","sectionName":""},"zones":[{"identifier":"49b25a18-a16f-449a-8196-168ad5faeeb7","widgets":[{"identifier":"c138a77a-f0e6-4189-aa74-933f7e68a429","type":"Kentico.Widget.RichText","variants":[{"identifier":"761994a4-6067-4865-a7bb-46f9758aa552","properties":{"content":"<p>When adding forms to websites, there may be occasions where you might prefer to restrict form respondents from making multiple form submissions. It could be that your form represents a method of signing up for an event, registering interest in a topic or webinar, or you might simply prefer that the same email address isn't associated with multiple form submissions.</p><p>This topic popped up recently as a question on the <a href="https://devnet.kentico.com/questions-answers" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Questions &amp; Answers</a> section of the <a href="https://devnet.kentico.com/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Xperience DevNet</a> portal. If you are new to developing Xperience websites, or you find you are having trouble implementing a certain feature of Xperience, then I highly recommend submitting questions on the Q&amp;A section of DevNet. You can get really good solutions and detailed explanations from the Xperience community, including answers from <a href="https://xperience.io/partnership/mvp-program" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Xperience MVPs</a> and members of the Kentico Support team.</p>"},"fieldIdentifiers":{"content":"a775cf9e-ba4d-4c53-bf23-ae593f619a11"}}]}]}],"fieldIdentifiers":{"sectionID":"11a55772-21db-4761-aa0c-055c7e93d267","sectionName":"e0cca912-6869-4feb-8156-babc1ddd275b"}},{"identifier":"6fbf4e81-9341-47a7-a9a9-bda2212de14b","type":"Goldfinch.ContentSection","properties":{"sectionID":"solution","sectionName":"The solution"},"zones":[{"identifier":"e9d4ae3e-22f4-4d27-a91a-286778ef4c10","widgets":[{"identifier":"9aa686a9-f2de-4b01-bed5-f30588d47272","type":"Kentico.Widget.RichText","variants":[{"identifier":"3bf7f921-c0d9-41f8-83e0-92d3a01a2799","properties":{"content":"<p>For this question in particular, I provided sample code which can be used in your Xperience MVC site. This module intercepts a form submission, checks for fields containing the keyword email, and compares the values submitted against values from other submissions to find a match. &nbsp;If it finds a match then the form submission is cancelled and an error is displayed, otherwise the form continues to process as you would expect. &nbsp;You can find the sample code below:</p>"},"fieldIdentifiers":{"content":"871d817a-fed8-46a9-a813-7eeadaa477b6"}}]},{"identifier":"95617da9-1a1c-4047-8b50-e4174ebade79","type":"Goldfinch.CodeBlockWidget","variants":[{"identifier":"1cbefa6c-124a-428f-9b25-ee1f3632cc97","properties":{"language":"csharp","code":"using CMS;
using CMS.DataEngine;
using CMS.OnlineForms;
using DancingGoat.GlobalEvents;
using System.Linq;

[assembly: RegisterModule(typeof(FormGlobalEventsModule))]
namespace DancingGoat.GlobalEvents
{
    public class FormGlobalEventsModule : Module
    {
        public FormGlobalEventsModule() : base("DancingGoat.FormGlobalEventsModule")
        {
        }

        protected override void OnInit()
        {
            base.OnInit();

            // Register custom events
            BizFormItemEvents.Insert.Before += Insert_Before;
        }

        private void Insert_Before(object sender, BizFormItemEventArgs e)
        {
            var item = e.Item;

            // Sanity check to ensure we actually have a bizform item.
            if (item == null)
            {
                return;
            }

            // Get all column names that contain email.
            var columnNames = item.ColumnNames.Where(x => x.ToLowerInvariant().Contains("email"));

            // Loop over all column names containing the keyword email.
            foreach (var columnName in columnNames)
            {
                // Get the submitted email address value.
                var email = item.GetStringValue(columnName, string.Empty);

                // Lookup the current bizform for submissions with the same field value.
                var existingEntry = BizFormItemProvider.GetItems(e.Item.BizFormClassName)
                    .Column(columnName)
                    .TopN(1)
                    .WhereEquals(columnName, email)
                    .FirstOrDefault();

                // If it already exists, cancel it (displays an error on the MVC site).
                if (existingEntry != null)
                {
                    e.Cancel();
                }
            }
        }
    }
}"},"fieldIdentifiers":{"language":"ac694e31-6743-4909-ba8b-3768a1883c6b","code":"126d948b-cd61-4456-b9d7-7fc89b8504d8"}}]}]}],"fieldIdentifiers":{"sectionID":"07953d50-bfef-4f74-ba1d-e7739022a8e7","sectionName":"aa49036a-dcca-45d3-b0b8-de5d8a7a842c"}}]}]}
